<http://www.grovemusic.com> (subscription required)\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMSLP2|work=Sorochinsky_Fair_(Mussorgsky,_Modest)|cname=''The Fair at Sorochyntsi''}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110604215918/http://www.ceo.spb.ru/libretto/classic/posle_glinki/sorochinskaya_yarmarka.zip Russian libretto in zip file for Word]\n*[http://www.jleonard.net/Sorochintsy_Fair.pdf English Libretto]\n\n{{Modest Mussorgsky}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fair at Sorochyntsi, The}}\n[[Category:Operas by Modest Mussorgsky]]\n[[Category:Operas by C\u00e9sar Cui]]\n[[Category:Russian-language operas]]\n[[Category:Operas based on works by Nikolai Gogol]]\n[[Category:1913 operas]]\n[[Category:Unfinished operas]]\n[[Category:Operas]]\n[[Category:Operas completed by others]]\n[[Category:Operas set in Ukraine]]\n", "name_user": "JackofOz", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eComposition history", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Fair_at_Sorochyntsi"}
{"title_page": "Nero-Film", "text_new": "'''Nero-Film AG''' was a German [[film production]] company founded in 1925 and based in [[Berlin]] during the [[Weimar era]].\n\n==History==\n\nThe company's name was derived from the names of its two founders: the letters \"NE\" stood for the name of the entrepreneur [[Heinrich Nebenzahl]], and the letters \"RO\" for the initials of director [[Richard Oswald]]. It was founded as ''Nero-Film GmbH'', a [[Gesellschaft mit beschr\u00e4nkter Haftung|limited liability company]], and was converted into an ''[[Aktiengesellschaft]]'', ''Nero-Film AG'', in 1927. \n\nUnder the influence of Nebenzahl's son [[Seymour Nebenzal]], Nero-Film was one of the most artistically ambitious production companies in Germany, and with directors like [[G.W. Pabst]] and [[Fritz Lang]] it produced a number of major films of the Weimar era, such as ''[[Pandora's Box (1929 film)|Pandora's Box]]'', ''[[Westfront 1918]]'', ''[[The Threepenny Opera (1931 film)|The Threepenny Opera]]'', ''[[M (1931 film)|M]]'', ''[[Kameradschaft]]'', ''[[L'Atlantide (1932 film)|L'Atlantide]]'' and ''[[The Testament of Dr. Mabuse]]''. In the film industry, the bourgeois-democratic Nero-Film and the proletarian [[Mezhrabpom-Film|Prometheus Film]] were the last bulwark against the rise of artistic [[Nazism]]. After the [[Machtergreifung|Nazi seizure of power in 1933]], Seymour Nebenzal was forced to emigrate, and Nero-Film AG was put out of business. ''[[The Testament of Dr. Mabuse]]'' became the first film censored by the [[Nazi]] government; Nebenzal and Director [[Fritz Lang]] appeared before Reich Minister of Propaganda [[Joseph Goebbels]], who ordered ''Mabuse'' destroyed and banned it from the Reich. \n\nNebenzal, using his American passport, fled that evening to [[Switzerland]] and then to [[France]], where he re-established his company as Production Nero Film and, among other French productions, collaborated with the Director [[Anatole Litvak]] to produce [[Mayerling]], a huge success for the star, [[Charles Boyer]].\nFleeing again to Los Angeles, as the Nazis invaded France, Nebenzal again re-established the company under the name of Nero Films Inc. Nebenzal's son, Harold, still manages the films in the Nero collection, including supervising a new print of his father's remake for Columbia Pictures in 1951 of [[M]], directed by [[Joseph Losey]] that was featured at [[Cannes]] Film Festival in 2016.\n\n==Selected filmography==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[The Prisoners of Shanghai|Die Gefangene von Shanghai]]'' (1927)\n* ''[[Das letzte Fort]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[Tragedy at the Royal Circus|Trag\u00f6die im Zirkus Royal]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[Pandora's Box (1929 film)|Die B\u00fcchse der Pandora]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[People on Sunday|Menschen am Sonntag]]'' (1930)\n* ''[[Westfront 1918|Vier von der Infanterie]]'' (1930)\n* ''[[Skandal um Eva]]'' (1930)\n* ''[[The Threepenny Opera (1931 film)|Die 3 Groschen-Oper]]'' (1931)\n* ''[[Ariane (film)|Ariane]]'' (1931)\n* ''[[M (1931 film)|M]]'' (1931)\n* ''[[Kameradschaft]]'' (1931)\n* ''[[L'Atlantide (1932 film)|L'Atlantide]]'' (1932) three versions: German, French, and English\n* ''[[Das Testament des Dr. Mabuse]]'' (1933)\n\nAs Production Nero Film\n* ''[[The Weaker Sex (1933 film)|Le Sexe faible]]'' (1933)\n* ''[[The Crisis is Over|La crise est finie]]'' (1934)\n* ''[[Parisian Life (1936 film)|La Vie parisienne]]'' (1936)\n* ''[[Mayerling (1936 film)|Mayerling]]'' (1936)\n* ''[[The Novel of Werther|Le Roman de Werther]]'' (1938)\n* ''[[Les Otages]]'' (1939)\n\nAs Nero Films Inc.\n* ''[[We Who Are Young]]'' (1940)\n* ''[[Hitler's Madman]]'' (1943)\n* ''[[Summer Storm (1944 film)|Summer Storm]]'' (1944)\n* ''[[Whistle Stop (1946 film)|Whistle Stop]]'' (1945)\n* ''[[The Chase (1946 film)|The Chase]]'' (1946)\n* ''[[Siren of Atlantis]]'' (1948)\n* ''[[M (1951 film)|M]]'' (1951)\n* ''[[Girl from Hong Kong|Bis zum Ende aller Tage]]'' (1961)\n{{div col end}}\n\n[[Seymour Nebenzal]]'s son [[Harold Nebenzal]] continued the three-generation tradition of Nero-Film through the production of such motion picture masterpieces as [[Cabaret]] and [[Gabriela, Cravo e Canela (film)|Gabriela]].\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book | last =Wottrich | first =Erika | title =M wie Nebenzahl: Nero-Filmproduktion zwischen Europa und Hollywood | publisher =Edition Text + Kritik | location =M\u00fcnchen | year =2002 | isbn =3883777102 }}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb company|0036089|Nero-Film AG}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.cinegraph.de/cgbuch/b14/einleitung.html|title=Nero - Filmproduktion zwischen Europa und Hollywood|accessdate=2012-07-31}} (in German)\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.cinegraph.de/kongress/01/k14_04.html|title=3 x Nebenzahl. Materialien zum 14. Internationalen Filmhistorischen Kongre\u00df, Hamburg, 15. - 18. November 2001|accessdate=2012-07-31}} (in German)\n\n[[Category:Film production companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Weimar culture]]\n[[Category:1925 establishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:1933 disestablishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1925]]\n[[Category:Media companies disestablished in 1933]]\n[[Category:Media in Berlin]]\n\n\n{{germany-org-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Nero-Film AG''' was a German [[film production]] company founded in 1925 and based in [[Berlin]] during the [[Weimar era]].\n\n==History==\n\nThe company's name was derived from the names of its two founders: the letters \"NE\" stood for the name of the entrepreneur [[Heinrich Nebenzahl]], and the letters \"RO\" for the initials of director [[Richard Oswald]]. It was founded as ''Nero-Film GmbH'', a [[Gesellschaft mit beschr\u00e4nkter Haftung|limited liability company]], and was converted into an ''[[Aktiengesellschaft]]'', ''Nero-Film AG'', in 1927. \n\nUnder the influence of Nebenzahl's son [[Seymour Nebenzal]], Nero-Film was one of the most artistically ambitious production companies in Germany, and with directors like [[G.W. Pabst]] and [[Fritz Lang]] it produced a number of major films of the Weimar era, such as ''[[Pandora's Box (1929 film)|Pandora's Box]]'', ''[[Westfront 1918]]'', ''[[The Threepenny Opera (1931 film)|The Threepenny Opera]]'', ''[[M (1931 film)|M]]'', ''[[Kameradschaft]]'', ''[[L'Atlantide (1932 film)|L'Atlantide]]'' and ''[[The Testament of Dr. Mabuse]]''. In the film industry, the bourgeois-democratic Nero-Film and the proletarian [[Mezhrabpom-Film|Prometheus Film]] were the last bulwark against the rise of artistic [[Nazism]]. After the [[Machtergreifung|Nazi seizure of power in 1933]], Seymour Nebenzal was forced to emigrate, and Nero-Film AG was put out of business. ''[[The Testament of Dr. Mabuse]]'' became the first film censored by the [[Nazi]] government; Nebenzal and Director [[Fritz Lang]] appeared before Reich Minister of Propaganda [[Joseph Goebbels]], who ordered ''Mabuse'' destroyed and banned it from the Reich. \n\nNebenzal, using his American passport, fled that evening to [[Switzerland]] and then to [[France]], where he re-established his company as Production Nero Film and, among other French productions, collaborated with the Director [[Anatole Litvak]] to produce [[Mayerling]], a huge success for the star, [[Charles Boyer]].\nFleeing again to Los Angeles, as the Nazis invaded France, Nebenzal again re-established the company under the name of Nero Films Inc. Nebenzal's son, Harold, still manages the films in the Nero collection, including supervising a new print of his father's remake for Columbia Pictures in 1951 of [[M]], directed by [[Joseph Losey]] that was featured at [[Cannes]] Film Festival in 2016.\n\n==Selected filmography==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[The Prisoners of Shanghai|Die Gefangene von Shanghai]]'' (1927)\n* ''[[Das letzte Fort]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[Tragedy at the Royal Circus|Trag\u00f6die im Zirkus Royal]]'' (1928)\n* ''[[Pandora's Box (1929 film)|Die B\u00fcchse der Pandora]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[People on Sunday|Menschen am Sonntag]]'' (1930)\n* ''[[Westfront 1918|Vier von der Infanterie]]'' (1930)\n* ''[[Skandal um Eva]]'' (1930)\n* ''[[The Threepenny Opera (1931 film)|Die 3 Groschen-Oper]]'' (1931)\n* ''[[Ariane (film)|Ariane]]'' (1931)\n* ''[[M (1931 film)|M]]'' (1931)\n* ''[[Kameradschaft]]'' (1931)\n* ''[[L'Atlantide (1932 film)|L'Atlantide]]'' (1932) three versions: German, French, and English\n* ''[[Das Testament des Dr. Mabuse]]'' (1933)\n\nAs Production Nero Film\n* ''[[The Weaker Sex (1933 film)|Le Sexe faible]]'' (1933)\n* ''[[The Crisis is Over|La crise est finie]]'' (1934)\n* ''[[Parisian Life (1936 film)|La Vie parisienne]]'' (1936)\n* ''[[Mayerling (1936 film)|Mayerling]]'' (1936)\n* ''[[The Novel of Werther|Le Roman de Werther]]'' (1938)\n* ''[[Les Otages]]'' (1939)\n\nAs Nero Films Inc.\n* ''[[We Who Are Young]]'' (1940)\n* ''[[Hitler's Madman]]'' (1943)\n* ''[[Summer Storm (1944 film)|Summer Storm]]'' (1944)\n* ''[[Whistle Stop (film)|Whistle Stop]]'' (1945)\n* ''[[The Chase (1946 film)|The Chase]]'' (1946)\n* ''[[Siren of Atlantis]]'' (1948)\n* ''[[M (1951 film)|M]]'' (1951)\n* ''[[Girl from Hong Kong|Bis zum Ende aller Tage]]'' (1961)\n{{div col end}}\n\n[[Seymour Nebenzal]]'s son [[Harold Nebenzal]] continued the three-generation tradition of Nero-Film through the production of such motion picture masterpieces as [[Cabaret]] and [[Gabriela, Cravo e Canela (film)|Gabriela]].\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book | last =Wottrich | first =Erika | title =M wie Nebenzahl: Nero-Filmproduktion zwischen Europa und Hollywood | publisher =Edition Text + Kritik | location =M\u00fcnchen | year =2002 | isbn =3883777102 }}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb company|0036089|Nero-Film AG}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.cinegraph.de/cgbuch/b14/einleitung.html|title=Nero - Filmproduktion zwischen Europa und Hollywood|accessdate=2012-07-31}} (in German)\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.cinegraph.de/kongress/01/k14_04.html|title=3 x Nebenzahl. Materialien zum 14. Internationalen Filmhistorischen Kongre\u00df, Hamburg, 15. - 18. November 2001|accessdate=2012-07-31}} (in German)\n\n[[Category:Film production companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Weimar culture]]\n[[Category:1925 establishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:1933 disestablishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1925]]\n[[Category:Media companies disestablished in 1933]]\n[[Category:Media in Berlin]]\n\n\n{{germany-org-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toWhistle Stop(link changed toWhistle Stop (1946 film)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nero-Film"}
